  "selection_reasoning": "Claude's KeyLeak-Sentinel is the strongest key-exfiltration concept: extremely rare plaintext-based trigger (~2^-64), minimal gate count, reuses existing datapath, and yields full AES-128 key recovery in 4 triggered encryptions. GPT4o's sequence-based trigger is interesting but less stealthy (multi-cycle FSM overhead and more likely to be hit by random control-signal fuzzing) and its payload is vague. To maximize variety per the challenge rubric, I kept Claude's key-leak as Trojan 1, and synthesized two additional distinct Trojans: (2) an integrity-attack Trojan that corrupts a single S-box lookup on a rare round+key-byte condition to silently produce wrong ciphertext (high integrity impact, tiny overhead, no key-leak overlap), and (3) an availability/denial Trojan that stalls the ready signal when a rare counter+input condition is met (DoS, different CIA axis). All three share sub-1% area overhead, use plaintext/internal-state triggers unreachable by KATs, and attack different CIA properties for scoring diversity.",
